<text>Good price, friendly staff, clean location with sufficient security.   Bring home owners or renter's insurance information as they require it (it may or may not cover the unit anyway).  If you do not have insurance they will require you buy insurance to cover the unit.  Also bring a strong lock as they also require one for entry.  If you do not bring one they will make you buy a lock.  So far so good; however, they need to have more carts on hand as there are only two available and they often are both being used.</text>< pictures>

My parents were putting their house on sale and needed to vacate within a week to have it remodeled and staged. Needless to say, they accumulated a ton of crap over the past 20+ years, and they needed a place to store it‚Äî fast.

I recommend Kings Kabobs to eat there or take home.

The beef kabob sandwich is really good it's on pita bread.

Grilled over a fire and I substitute hummus with the vinegar, oil & spice salad dressing.

Nothing fancy in fact it's literally a hole in the wall with 2 small serving windows in the side of the building. A couple of patio tables to eat or you can eat inside a couple of doors West.

Absolutely nothing fancy simply great food. Friends who have ordered other item menus are equally impressed< /Review>

< text>
Excellent food at good price.

Truly a hole in the wall because there are 2 windows in the side of the building to order from.

There is a small two table patio to eat but mostly take out. There is a small coffee shop/restaurant two doors down where you can eat inside.

This is one of those neat littleplaces which does what it does well.

I recommend the beef kabob sandwich.<//text>

As I googled the nearest Thai sport massage, Thai Sport Bodyworks, the closest one at that time popped up and I decided to give it a try. With varying issues from sore back and shoulders from constant lifting to tingling in hands, sciatic pains from years of abusing my body in the military, I can truly say that I am a regular at these types of pain relief establishments. Acupuncture, chiro, massages, water therapy, you name it, I do them all. I was very glad that I visited TSB on that day,  because this is where I met Zasha. Although I had been to a lot of Thai sport massages all over the states and outside the country, I have never had anyone as thorough and attentive as Zasha. She does not just go through the motion like everyone else. She knows you are there for a reason so she listens, she remembers, and she asks a lot of questions on what you need work on at each and every visit and massaged accordingly. The first time she worked on me, I noticed that I felt differently from when others worked on me. To confirm that I was not being biased, I had to go see other therapists elsewhere just to compare, and in my opinion, she is one of the best ones out there! She genuinely cares about her clients. Most of all, one can easily tell that she is the type of person that not only enjoys her job, but really takes pleasure in helping people, and so I always recommend Zasha to my friends and family.</review>

< Text>
I was in desperate need of a massage, with a six-week project finally over, but I didn‚Äôt want to go to the corporate-style, assembly line massage franchises that seem to be crowding out the ‚Äòauthentic experience‚Äô. So, I did some exploring and came up with a few massage businesses that were of interest. The one that struck me as ‚Äòstand-out‚Äô was a recently opened place in Rancho Bernardo called Thai Sport Bodyworks. I scheduled an appointment on-line within my scheduling constraints. Easy enough, but the actual experience far exceeded my expectations.

The reception area is warm, welcoming and inviting. The staff is enthusiastic, knowledgeable and friendly. They really seem to sincerely care about your problems and concerns and are more than helpful in recommending, but also dissuading, services that may not be right for you. The therapy rooms are authentic Thai, cozy and intimate. The subtle fragrances, muted lighting, and ethereal background music are idyllic, and are the ultimate enhancements to an already comfortable and relaxed atmosphere. You are swept into the prefect mood, mind and body, for one of the best massage experiences ever.

Maya was my therapist. I chose the Thai Sport massage, their special version of Thai massage. Though she is petite in stature; she is strong, but with a subtle touch and technique, and possesses a vast knowledge of anatomy, physiology, and body kinetics. She was able to communicate with me in an open and accessible way, starting out with a lighter touch and moving toward progressively deeper pressure, in a suitably adapted and appropriate manner, with my stiff, tight, sensitive lower back and shoulders yielding to her firm pressure, loosening and releasing knots, muscle tension and fatigue.

Although other Thai massages that I‚Äôve had are way too ‚Äòdeep-tissue‚Äô and didn‚Äôt adequately address my upper back and shoulders, this massage was definitely not that. It was the ideal fusion of East and West massage techniques, and very much the therapeutic massage that my body was longing for. The essential oils treatment was included. I had the Soothe, but there are others, depending on your needs. The add-ons I chose were heated stone treatment and the cupping, for different impairments and dysfunctions, but I highly recommend both.

Working a computer or in meetings all day, leaves my body cramped, sore and fatigued. Though I spend as much free time as I can in the gym, on my bike, or on the trails, it seems to never be enough to compensate for the time spent ‚Äòsitting‚Äô. I have finally found a sports therapy and massage spa that fits my schedule and my budget for bi-weekly or even weekly visits. This time I had the 90 minutes Thai Sport, but am eagerly looking forward to trying the neuromuscular, therapeutic massages, and their dynamic stretching services. As an added benefit they have a full 3-D Body Scanner that syncs up with the ‚Äòcloud‚Äô to enable me to track my progress and improvements over time and share that information with my personal trainer.

I can‚Äôt commend the staff enough. They are hospitable, eager, and knowledgeable. The spa is well designed, with a pleasant feel, discriminating taste, and an aura of heartfelt sense of well-being. And Maya was extraordinary! The entire encounter is the best massage experience I have had, ever. Five-star, and I highly recommend Thaisport!</Text>

I'm very happy that they expanded to Rancho Bernardo. It's closer to my work and home when compared to their Sorrento Valley location. The RB location is bigger, brighter, and roomier.

I went to many other massage places before finding Thai Sport Bodyworks. Most other massage places do not care about your body and give you the same genetic massage they give everyone else. More personalized massage franchises have terrible business models/payment policies. I would know because I used to be a member of a well known massage franchise, but ended my membership after paying for months which I did not need a massage.

Which brings me to this place and Lawani. I found Lawani after I sprained my right shoulder in 2013. I had a lot of aches and pain when moving it. I couldn't believe how much better my shoulder felt after the initial visit. It felt like I finally got my shoulder back. Then a few months down the road, I pulled my hamstring which caused sciatica. I was doing physical therapy for the hamstring/sciatica, but I truly believed it was a combination of a chiropractor's adjustments and Lawani's massages that finally cured the sciatica. The Kaiser physical therapy was a waste of money.

I'm very happy that I found Lawani. I bring myself in and pay only when my body needs maintenance. Gone are the days when I paid for a generic massage. Also, gone are the days when I used to pay a monthly massage subscriptions to a massage franchise. Now I pay for great massages only when I need them. I have recommended this place to my friends and co-workers.

I'm so happy to have known Lawani since the time she used to be located inside of a small gym, but now they have 2 locations! New location, same great owner.</Review>

< Text>
Small place in a small strip of stores. Not fine dining atmosphere or for hipsters, but simple, clean, and great food at an average price. Chili Chutney started in this space too and did very well. As most others here said, food is great and the people are extremely friendly. Small menu, but hey, the name is "Taste of Kabob" :) Kabobs are tender and flavorful. Salad has a nice lemon tang. Bread is fresh and hot. Overall a very pleasant experience. If you like Persian food or want to try some tasty chicken or beef, go here. (Great hot tea was not free as someone else said but I have no doubt the friendly owners occasionally offer something on the house.)<//Text>

<Rating>5</Rating><Review>I know good Persian food, and this place has it. From the traditional Ghormeh Sabzi  to the  familiar kabobs, you are eating the authentic thing here, and it's delicious. The restaurant itself is small and unassuming with limited seating inside and a few tables outside. When we ate here, several customers picked up orders, so take-out appears to be a popular choice. The owners are friendly and make sure you are enjoying yourself. Tea is excellent and served with traditional sugar cubes. My daughter (3) was also a huge fan, so your picky toddler may have met their match here. Persian food isn't exactly rare here in OC, but this is the best I've had outside of LA, and that's saying something. Fine dining it is not, but if you're in it for the food alone, you will be most impressed with what you eat here.</Review><Pics>None<//Pics>< gmapID>

< Review>
Amazing experience!
I am just another software guy in the bay area, looking for ways to fix an issue I had with my BMW 340i. I was exploring auto services in and around SVL/MTV and came across Lozano. Usually when I see such positive reviews (all close to 5 stars), I am a little skeptical and always think the reviews are faked of sort. Either way, I decided to give this place a shot.

My BMW's under car shield had torn apart and BMW quoted high fees to replace them. When I went there, Vince first came out to inspect the car. Vince took the car inside, put it on the machine that lifted my car up. With this, we were able to clearly see what the damage was.

Vince and Troy together spent time removing the torn parts out so that my car was at least in a drivable condition. They spent 15 minutes, passionately explaining various parts of the undercover shield. After that, they told me precisely which parts I needed to replace, which was fewer than what BMW had asked for.

After this was done, Vince just lowered my car and said I was set to go, NOT EVENING ASKING FOR ANY $. I was stunned and very pleasantly surprised. They never charge you without knowing any upfront costs. In this case, I felt they definitely deserved to be paid so I decided I would come back to them with the new parts and pay them then.

As promised, I came back with the new parts I purchased from BMW and once again, Vince and his team fixed it for me at a very low cost.

If you are looking for no BS, perfect pricing and passionate set of folks, this is the place to go!

In picture, you can see Troy helping me out :)

Kudos to Troy and Vince!

Thank you Lozano :)<//Review>

< Review>
I've been coming here for years. One of the first things I noticed was how clean they were. They have two male technicians and about 5-6 females. Everyone is wonderful but my favorite is Kim. They get busy in spurts and are very honest when you walk in how long the wait will be. The reason I have stayed with them for this long is because I value my time and appointments and so do they which is VERY rare in this industry.

Only downfall would be you can only leave a cash tip. Doesn't matter now, I'm used to it but at first I would forget and feel horribly guilty lol.

They definitely do not rush even if they are busy. Prices are also probably the lowest I have found. They are very fair and honest. Love them all to pieces.</Review>

<username>Sarah Coonan</username><pics>None< /pics>< Rating>
3</Rating>
< review>
This was my first visit to this salon. They had decent reviews on Google which made me choose them over the place I normally go but is a bit farther from me.

I went ahead and made a same day appointment. They were busy when I arrived, and they remained very busy during my visit. There was only the option for pedicure and spa pedicure, both of which were $18. There are no add-ons (extra scrubs, callous removers, etc).

The calf and foot massage, though brief, felt very nice. It was a short pedicure, lasting approximately 30 min of in chair time, not including drying time.

If you're looking for a very basic, quick and inexpensive pedicure, this is a good option.

However, I don't think I'll be coming back. I enjoy the add-ons and don't like feeling rushed.<//review>

<rating>5< /rating><Review>Been coming here since 2015 almost 6 years! I have 2 reviews on Yelp. Don't mind doing another considering due to covid it's handled differently of course. Only 3 customers are allowed to be inside. Once you enter you can add your name and number as well as what service you will be getting (optional of course) they will notify you either call or text once it's your turn. They disinfect after every customer. Since I've been coming here the owner has been working non stop especially during the holidays. Customer service is always extraordinary, they always ask first how you would like them before starting unless they already know. I always make sure to tip extra when I'm able to because she deserves it. Yes sometimes there is a wait but that just proves that it's worth it. I've seen people call ahead to see if there is a line. < Text>
Do not buy a car from this dealer unless you live within a few miles of the dealership.

I have never experienced such terrible customer service.. the shocker is that they are a BMW dealer so we expected so much more. What a disappointment.

To start with we were out of state buyers. They do not like out of state buyers because apparently it is too much work. We were very surprised - as was BMW USA. We have purchased cars from out of state before and even shipped a car from Hawaii and never had any issues.

My Dad worked a car dealership for over 30 years. Every customer had value and out of state buyers were a large part of their business. Considering BMW does not have a presence in smaller communities, selling cars to people who are not local shouldn't be a new thing; it seems a bit discriminatory as well.

They FINALLY agreed to sell us the car....after weeks of hassle. Then we could not get them to send any paperwork or the shipping information.
We asked, and asked - to no avail. They requested and received our cashier's check - issued directly from the banks account. Cashier's checks are equal to cash where I am from, but this was like the Twilight Zone because they held up the deal for another 10 days while the check "cleared their account."

They also refused to sell us the car if there was a lienholder...apparently it was too much paperwork. Cash deals only if you live out of state.

Still no paperwork, no shipping information...no car. At this point we were six weeks into this all-consuming hassle. We tried to remain friendly and professional , but things had gotten really ridiculous.
Request after request for shipping information only to be told they were working on it. Their constant excuse for the lack of timeliness? "That is why we don't sell to out of state buyers."

Absolutely shocking.

I noticed that they like to discredit people who post bad reviews so for the record:
My daughter was the person trying to purchase this car, Riverside BMW agree to sell it to her and happily took her money.......this is called a CONTRACT.

This is a legitimate review - I generally do not write bad reviews because it is unfortunate that people always choose to complain and not compliment. This business has not earned the one star that I gave them - I wish I could give them zero stars but unfortunately that is not possible.

...The car finally showed up last Thursday....approximately 2 months after her first conversation with the dealer.< /Text>

Soooo.... I had a reading of a right brake light malfunction on my beloved BMW 435i, aka, the Weekend Whip. Fabian Hernandez was assigned as my Aftersales Consultant.

Mr. Hernandez was probably the absolute best representative of any car maintenance situation I have ever encountered. "How do you mean?‚Äù you ask. For me, going to the dealership, any dealership for ANY reason brings me a dark shade of red-zoned anxiety. Note that this is my third BMW. Also note that it's the car, not the people, that keep me laced in the comforts of these ultimate driving machines. This day was different. For starters, Mr. Hernandez was respectful, smiled (seems to be a lost art), explained then confirmed that I understood what he shared without being condescending or rushed (and away went round one of my anxiety). His follow-up was very commendable as well (the Weekend Whip stayed overnight) - pleasant, detailed voice mail and texts to keep me updated on the progress of the repair. Now, you may be thinking, "That's what an Aftersales Consultant is *supposed* to do". Yeah, but many of you know that is definitely not always the case.

My Sweetie, who drives something comparably a few pegs below interesting, came along and let me know throughout the appointment that the level of service and attention far exceeded his expectations. He was right.

The second round of my anxiety was dismissed when Mr. Hernandez shared the good and great news that the warranty covered my repair. Something out of his control of influence, but I give him credit for being the messenger.

A shout out to BMW of Riverside. Thank you for good and great service.

~Dr. Gina M. Newton
& her beloved BMW 435i (aka, the Weekend Whip)< /text>

< text>
I leased a 2020 BMW 330i from BMW of Riverside, which was a previous loaner vehicle. I went through a car broker to lease this vehicle and the vehicle was delivered to my home in Sylmar, CA, by a dealer staff (~80 miles). I was very excited when I received the vehicle and so to my disadvantage, I did not do a thorough inspection before signing my paperwork, and being a workday, I only took it around the block (<0.5 mile) and immediately parked it in my garage.

The following day I had a better look at the vehicle, inside and out, and noted a few faults. 1) The windshield had a crack; 2) there was hot glue-like stains in the center console area (3 specific areas ‚Äì including the shift knob); 3) a speaker sounded busted; 4) both front wheels had curb damage but were repaired by the dealer (poorly).

I reached out to the broker and asked about issues 1, 2, and 3. He said he will get in touch with the dealer. BMW of Riverside told my broker to take the vehicle in to inspect the issues. I scheduled an appointment and took the vehicle in. The dealer fixed the speaker issue (3) under warranty and said if I wanted the windshield (1) and console stains (2) fixed, it would be charged to me at a price of $2,500 and $1,600, respectively. They are trying to put these damages on me stating it passed inspection before being delivered to me.

To note, I saw two dealer employees inspect my vehicle before accepting it in for service and neither noted the issues until I pointed them out. I am not saying that staff is incompetent, but I noted that they are not thorough.

I am very disappointed how this dealer has and is treating a loyal customer by blaming their mistakes on me and will never shop at BMW of Riverside again and will encourage all of my friends and family the same.<//text>

< Review>
Resident from Canada, took my BMW cross-country. I was staying nearby this dealership. They took care of my vehicle, had it serviced and washed during my two visits. They were able to honor everything BMW CA would have done, it was a unique situation, but was well handled by the service department.

Almost lost trust in my vehicle after malfunctioning in the middle of traffic, but after my final service before departing for a 30 hour drive, drove it with no more problems. Job well done, Thanks to Fabian Hernandez and the team for making sure my car would make it back to Canada.

Exemplary customer service. Before and after, more BMW dealerships should look up to this place.<//Review>

She eagerly answered every question I had (there were many) and coordinated my out-of-state purchase seamlessly.

Beyond her sales professionalism, she was a knowledgeable and passionate BMW/motoring enthusiast, which is far rarer than you think. This was the icing on the cake.

The car had no hidden issues, and they were fair on pricing.

Gianna made things so easy and satisfying that I‚Äôd be willing to buy another one-way plane ticket and endure the 20-hour drive back home again, for the right car.

If you know or think you want a BMW and a positive buying experience, call BMW of Riverside and specifically demand Gianna. She will see that you‚Äôre taken care of!<//review>

Fool me once, shame on you; fool me twice, shame on me. Fool me three times:
It all started a year and a half ago when I first brought in my 2015 328xi Gran Turismo for service at BMW of Riverside. I went in for a change in brake fluid after receiving notification on my vehicle, and after the service was performed, the BMW Riverside Service Department would not release me my vehicle. I was told ‚Äúmy brakes were too low to release me the vehicle‚Äù, and that an $1,100 brake rotor and pad service would need to be performed. I declined, as the price quoted is more than what I was given elsewhere such as Sterling and Crevier and wanted the service performed either of these locations; they held my vehicle hostage and would not release me my vehicle, even though I had driven it there in the first place. A week goes by as I plead with the Service Department to release me MY property, with no give. I cave, as I needed my vehicle for work, and have the vehicle towed elsewhere at my expense. Strike one for withholding my personal possessions that weren‚Äôt even initially purchased at this location.

A couple months go by, and my vehicle starts exhibiting strange behavior. I would receive the dreaded infamous ‚ÄúDrivetrain Malfunction‚Äù notification on my vehicle‚Äôs screen, and the vehicle would go into ‚Äúlimp mode‚Äù with full engine output not available. Turning the car off and on would temporarily reset the vehicle back to normal, until the issue would reappear a few hundred miles later. Foolishly after the first incident with this dealership, I take my car back for service at BMW Riverside being that is the slightly-closest location. I, like many this day and age, have an OBD II reader and a companion app that can read BMW diagnostic and error codes that are shown to the dealer when they check on your vehicle. The error codes stored in the vehicle stated that cylinders 2 and 4 were shutting down due to not receiving enough fuel: a mechanical malfunction. I have an extended warranty on my vehicle that covers the full cost of repair for all mechanical faults around engine components with a small deductible. I mention this mechanical fault to the service representative when first dropping off my vehicle for service; I sign for the diagnostic thinking, when I get my vehicle serviced it‚Äôll go towards the repair cost anyway. After diagnosing the vehicle, the service rep states that there are NO MECHANICAL FAULTS with the vehicle, and that a software update to the cars ECU would alleviate the issue. I contest him, as the codes stored in the car state that a mechanical fault is present. Beyond that, when the vehicle goes in this limp state, you can physically feel the cars vibrations as the cylinders shut down, and can hear the fuel pump malfunctioning. The Service Manager at the time, Travis,  was very firm in keeping the diagnosis as a software issue in order to avoid having my warranty cover the cost of the repair, and instead wanted to force me to pay out of pocket by misdiagnosing the issue as electronic-related. The service rep once again holds my vehicle hostage until I pay $200 for an incorrect diagnosis; seeing it as a lost cause to contend any further, I pay the full $500 for the diagnosis and ECU update in the hopes that it will fix my issue. Fast forward 2 weeks after I pay for the ECU update, and my vehicle once again goes into limp mode as I‚Äôm commuting to work on the freeway, with the same ‚ÄúDrivetrain Malfunction‚Äù error present.. This time turning the vehicle off and on wouldn‚Äôt return it to normal,  and the vehicle needed to be towed to BMW Riverside, once again at my expense. This time, the service manager Travis acknowledge his mistake, and replaced the low fuel pump on my vehicle to actually fix the issue for no more than the $500 I had already paid. Ultimately, this situation cost me $400 more than it should have as it was a warranty-covered issue, plus the cost of tows and work missed. But it doesn‚Äôt end there: I dropped off my vehicle to BMW Riverside -I have oil dripping from underneath my car.< /Review>
